      "content": "Historians generally agree that a combination of strategies was most effective, as it allowed the movement to respond to changing circumstances and gain momentum. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s non-violent approach helped to initially gain widespread public support and ultimately led to significant legislative change. Meanwhile, more radical approaches, such as the Black Power Movement, while ultimately contributing to the movement's impact, were sometimes seen as divisive and detracting from the broader coalition-building that King's leadership facilitated.",
